what is a tourist spot blog? give an example

That's a great question!

A "tourist spot blog" is essentially a type of travel blog that specifically focuses on chronicling trips, destinations, and providing in-depth guides, recommendations, and personal insights about places people want to visit.

Instead of just being a personal diary, a good tourist spot blog post combines:

  1. Personal Storytelling: The writer's unique experience and perspective.

  2. Practical Information: "How-to" details like ticket prices, best times to visit, transportation tips, and hidden gems.

  3. Visual Inspiration: High-quality photos (or descriptions that evoke vivid imagery) to make readers want to go.

1. Simplest Method: Static Hosting (Great for School Projects)

The easiest way to get your HTML file visible online is using a static hosting service. These services take your HTML, CSS, and JavaScript files and serve them directly over the internet.

OptionHow It WorksBest For
GitHub PagesYou push the tumauini_blog.html file to a public GitHub repository. GitHub automatically hosts it for free at an address like yourusername.github.io/repository-name.Free, reliable, great for portfolio and school work, and teaches version control.
Netlify / VercelYou connect these services to your GitHub repository. They build and deploy your site automatically every time you make a change.Modern, very fast, and incredibly easy setup (often just a few clicks).

To do this:

  1. Save the content of tumauini_blog.html as a file named index.html on your computer.

  2. Follow the setup steps for your chosen platform (GitHub Pages is a great starting point).

2. Shared Web Hosting (For Existing Websites)

If you already have a paid web hosting service (like Bluehost, GoDaddy, etc.) and a registered domain name, you simply need to upload the file via FTP (File Transfer Protocol).

  • You upload tumauini_blog.html to a specific folder on your web server (e.g., /public_html/blogs/).

  • The blog post will then be accessible at an address like: www.yourdomain.com/blogs/tumauini_blog.html.

3. Using a Content Management System (CMS)

If you want the blog to be part of a larger site with user comments, an author dashboard, and automatic styling, you would use a CMS like WordPress or Jekyll.

  • WordPress: You would typically copy and paste the text content, separating the headings and paragraphs into the WordPress editor, and then upload your images (uploaded:5a4ded75-66e8-4fed-82bc-5de689a5dc41.jfif, etc.) directly into the media library.

  • Jekyll: This is a static site generator that is excellent for blogs hosted on GitHub Pages. You would convert your content into a Markdown file (.md) that uses a special YAML front matter (metadata like title, date, author) and Jekyll would build the final HTML page for you.

2. Create a New Repository

  • Click the "+" icon in the top right corner and select New repository.

  • Repository name: Choose a name for your project (e.g., tumauini-blog-project).

  • Description (Optional): Add a short summary.

  • Access: Ensure it is set to Public (required for free GitHub Pages hosting).

  3. Commit the changes (save).

4. Enable GitHub Pages

  1. On your repository page, click the Settings tab.

    • Ensure the folder is set to / (root).
